##################################################
#      IMPORTANT                                 #
##################################################
- this version of CPSMailBoxer relies on a modified
  version of MailBoxer 3.1 that is available on dev2
  in /home/zopes/_packages/MailBoxer-3.1-nuxeo.tar.gz

- if ou do not use this version but the genuine 3.1
  you will certainl get mime_decode_header errors


##################################################
#      CPSMailBoxer and other CPS Products       #
##################################################

- CPSMailBoxer is not declared as an allowed content type for
  any other portal type. So if you want it to be available e.g.
  in Workspace, you need to manually add it (either throught the
  ZMI and through your installer)

- Action Status History should not be available for CPSMailBoxer
  and CPSMailBoxerFolder. Again, this should be set manually either
  through the ZMI or you own installer/external method (examples of
  how this is done for other portal types are available in CPSForum
  and CPSDefault)

##################################################
#      Setting up aliases (Linux/postfix)        #
##################################################

CPSMailBoxer features two options for redirecting incoming emails :
- method A: create hardcoded aliases for each list address
- method B: create a single alias that handles different lists

Details about the two methods are based on a Linux+Postfix configuration for
handling incoming emails.

#########################
# method A:
#########################
1) copy file smtp2zope.py in a location that can be reached by postfix and check
   r/x rights on the file (e.g. in /usr/local/sbin/)

2) edit /etc/aliases and add a line following this model:
   liste_name: "|/usr/local/sbin/smtp2zope.py http://hostname:port/cps/workspaces/mailing_lists/liste_id/manage_mailboxer"

   where list_name is the list's email address (as set in your CPSMailBoxer instance)

   example for list object 'liste1' whose address is test_list@example.net :
       test_list: "|/usr/local/sbin/smtp2zope.py http://hostname:port/cps/workspaces/mailing_lists/liste1/manage_mailboxer"


3) run command newaliases

#########################
# method B:
#########################
1) copy file smtp2zope.py in a location that can be reached by postfix and check
   r/x rights on the file (e.g. in /usr/local/sbin/)

2) this method is more complicated as you have to create regexp based rules to handle different list addresses with the same alias

     e.g. to redirect all incoming mails addressed to lists ending in @lists.example.org,

     - edit /etc/postfix/virtual and add a rule to redirect all wanted addresses to the same alias

         @lists.example.org alias@hostname

     - and then edit /etc/aliases on hostname

         alias: "|/usr/local/sbin/smtp2zope.py http://hostname:port/cps/nmb_mapper"


3) run command 'postmap /etc/postfix/virtual' and then run command 'newaliases'

4) with this method, it is not necessary to create new aliases each time you create
   a new CPSMailBoxer that manages lists ending in e.g. @lists.example.org since 
   the mapping to the actual mailboxer object is handled dynamically by nmb_mapper
   instead of being hardcoded in the alias (as done in method A)



##################################################
#      Problems                                  #
##################################################
- if there are workflow-related problems when processing (archival of) a mail,
  make sure that CPSMailBoxerFolder has no workflow associated with it

- when upgrading MailBoxer (e.g. from 2.2.6 to 3.1), be sure to check that the
  version of smtp2zope you use to redirect mails is the on included in the new
  version of MailBoxer


 